Section 2.6.2 lists the popcount code:


    // pc[i] is the population count of i.
    var pc [256]byte
    
    func init() {
    	for i := range pc {
    		pc[i] = pc[i/2] + byte(i&amp;1)
    	}
    }
    
    // PopCount returns the population count (number of set bits) of x.
    func PopCount(x uint64) int {
    	return int(pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(0*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(1*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(2*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(3*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(4*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(5*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(6*8))] +
    		pc[byte(x&gt;&gt;(7*8))])
    }

This is an optimized version. `init` builds a lookup table of the population count (number of bits set to 1 in binary representation) for each possible byte, and `PopCount` adds that up for each byte out of the 8 bytes in a `uint64`.

The exercises following this section ask you to implement different variants of pop count and compare their performance to that snippet.

Specifically, exercise 2.4 asks about shifting through 64 bit positions. Given a 64-bit int, you run a loop that iterates 64 times, in each iteration examining a different bit of the `uint64`. It counts all the bits it sees are set to 1. You&#39;re supposed to implement this and compare performance.

