Netty itself doesn&#39;t remove handlers form the Pipeline. `ChannelPipeline` is gathered by GC as regular Java object when it is no longer used (channel holding `ChannelPipeline` is closed).

So either you do that in your code (but you don&#39;t) or pipeline is destroyed with the channel.
As you are doing load testing my suggestion is next:

- You create load on your server;
- Test client can&#39;t handle enough load and closes some of the connections (pretty common situation during high load tests);
- Netty see that connection is closed and removes the channel (and pipeline with it) and it is gathered with GC;
- As a result you still have the context that is references to the removed channel;

&gt; Under load, this ChannelHandlerContext &quot;becomes removed&quot;, and hence
&gt; the submitted write task cannot, when run by the event loop, take
&gt; place.

This is expected. Channel could become unavailable at any moment. So if you delegate the task to some thread pool you should check that channel is still active/writable or you can use `ChannelFuture` from the `write()` operation for that.

**Update:**

You have multiple options depending on what you need. You can check the channel is writable before the actual write:

    if (ctx.channel().isWritable()) {
        //write
    }

You can check the `ChannelFuture` for the write operation result:

    ChannelFuture cf = ctx.writeAndFlush();
    //cf has a bunch of method + listeners that you can use

You can use `ChannelPromise`  as well and override required method.

Netty very flexible and provides many possible flows.

